rticles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"tone/extract","webTitle":"Extracts","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/extract","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/extract","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"id":"books/2015/dec/17/the-book-collector-alice-thompson-review","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"type":"article","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"The Book Collector by Alice Thompson review – elegant and shocking entertainment","webPublicationDate":"2015-12-17T16:00:15Z","fields":{"wordcount":"682","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4f29d","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p>Modern celebrity examples warn us that a marriage described as “fairytale” is usually anything but. What happens after “happily ever after” is a question addressed in Alice Thompson’s seventh novel, and a book of Hans Christian Andersen’s fairytales provides the central motif.</p> <p>Orphaned Violet is approached at a cafe by a mysterious man who leaves, as if by chance, a business card for a second-hand bookshop called, with gothic appropriateness, Looking Glass. The first book Violet opens on arriving at the shop is an anatomy textbook with a drawing of a flayed woman. “The muscular tissue of the woman’s breasts were like the elaborate swirling of cartographic mountains.” “They’re just drawings,” she concludes, and replaces the volume on the shelf.</p> <p>The shop’s proprietor, Lord Archibald Murray, turns out to be the mysterious man from the cafe, and they swiftly marry. “Their romance had been like a fairytale. If only she could work out which fairytale it was, it would somehow help her.” Will it be <a href=\"http://www.readbookonline.net/readOnLine/121/\" title=\"\"><em>The Red Shoes</em></a>, whose heroine is danced to death, punished by her worldly thoughts, or <a href=\"http://www.authorama.com/english-fairy-tales-29.html\" title=\"\"><em>Mr Fox</em></a>, whose wife is enjoined to “Be bold, be bold, but not too bold”? Or maybe it’s a modern tale, such as <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2008/aug/09/4\" title=\"\"><em>Rebecca</em></a>, with its saturnine hero obsessed with a dead wife and a ghastly secret.</p> <p><em>The Book Collector</em> is purportedly set in the Edwardian era, though I wouldn’t have guessed that without reading the blurb. Jarring elements include the liberal use of makeup, particularly plum lipstick, which sounds a bit Revlon for the period. Actually, the setting is simply “the past”, before cars and telephones, or widespread notions about women’s rights.</p> <p>If the male gothic tradition involves the violation of social norms and taboos by male will, in the female tradition the male transgressor becomes, as <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/nov/27/gothic-fiction-divided-selves\" title=\"\">Alison Milbank</a> puts it in <em>The Handbook of Gothic Literature</em>, “the villain, whose authoritative reach as patriarch, abbot or despot, seeks to entrap the heroine … [threatening] death or rape.” Of course Archie can’t legally rape his wife, but does something horrifying lurk under his bland smile?</p> <p>The gothic genre is known for its florid language, as well as liberal use of motifs such as the cave, the isolated house, the asylum and the forbidden text, all present here. But Thompson’s style is largely plain, unadorned, matter-of-fact, as Violet struggles to hold on to her sanity and distinguish reality from illusion. She is an appealing heroine and not just a suffering cypher, able to make sharp observations about the people around her, before laudanum and medical procedures take the sting out of her soul. For one thing, she is sensual, eagerly pursuing her own pleasure, curious about male and female bodies.</p> <p>One of her observations concerns the orderliness of all about her. The doctors and her husband have the world sewn up between them. “Was there a hidden system to her marriage she hadn’t realised, also?” The masculine world may be coherent and logical, she realises, but there is not enough room in it for emotion, intuition and humanity.</p> <p>In the room of a sinister stranger, Violet contemplates a stuffed fox who, while not the kind of talking animal we meet in fairytales, still has something crucial to impart: “He looked alert, but for the fact he was dead.” Her husband, who loves physical books much more than the ideas in them, is dead at the core.</p> <p><em>The Book Collector</em> is an exercise in using traditional tropes and leaving whopping clues lying around, while still creating unease and suspense. Perhaps Thompson resolves and reveals too much at the end – I like to be left in doubt, myself – but she has created an elegant and bloodily shocking entertainment.</p> <p>• To order <em>The Book Collector </em>for £7.19 go to <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/349644/s/the-book-collector/?utm_source=editoriallink&amp;utm_medium=merch&amp;utm_campaign=article\" title=\"\">bookshop.theguardian.com</a> or call 0330 333 6846. Free UK p&amp;p over £10, online orders only. Phone orders min p&amp;p of £1.99.</p>","productionOffice":"UK","hasStoryPackage":"false","trailText":"With its gothic motifs, this dark portrait of a ‘fairytale’ marriage is full of mystery and suspense","headline":"The Book Collector by Alice Thompson review – elegant and shocking entertainment","byline":"Suzi Feay","commentable":"true","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/146772f03bbb032ca47fba065fc2c2051a2da445/0_303_1616_969/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-01-29T12:56:00Z","standfirst":"<p>With its gothic motifs, this dark portrait of a ‘fairytale’ marriage is full of mystery and suspense</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/dec/17/the-book-collector-alice-thompson-review","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2015/dec/17/the-book-collector-alice-thompson-review","sectionName":"Books","elements":[{"id":"146772f03bbb032ca47fba065fc2c205