nName":"Children's books","references":[]},{"id":"books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","webTitle":"Children and teenagers","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/childrens-books-8-12-years","webTitle":"Children's books: 8-12 years","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/childrens-books-8-12-years","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/childrens-books-8-12-years","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/teen-books","webTitle":"Teen books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/teen-books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/teen-books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","webTitle":"Books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/childrens-books-7-and-under","webTitle":"Children's books: 7 and under","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/childrens-books-7-and-under","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/childrens-books-7-and-under","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"culture/culture","webTitle":"Culture","type":"keyword","sectionId":"culture","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","sectionName":"Culture","references":[]},{"id":"books/picture-books","webTitle":"Picture books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/picture-books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/picture-books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"type/gallery","webTitle":"Gallery","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/inpictures","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/gallery","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"id":"books/2015/dec/17/very-rare-hans-christian-andersen-illustration-up-for-auction-watercolour","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"type":"article","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Very rare Hans Christian Andersen illustration sold at auction","webPublicationDate":"2015-12-17T13:35:15Z","fields":{"wordcount":"493","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4f6kh","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p>A “very rare” watercolour illustrating Hans Christian Andersen’s fairytale about the nightingale that sings for the Emperor of China has been sold at auction to an American collector for £32,000.</p> <p>By the acclaimed Danish illustrator Kay Nielsen, the image was painted in 1923 to illustrate The Nightingale in a collection of Andersen’s stories published by Hodder &amp; Stoughton in 1924. Works by Nielsen, who is also known for <a href=\"https://archive.org/stream/hanselgretelothe00grimrich#page/20/mode/2up\">his illustrations of the Brothers Grimm fairytales</a> but who died in poverty in 1957, are very rare, according to Chris Albury at Dominic Winter Auctioneers. Dominic Winter, which is auctioning the painting, called Nielsen “one of the greatest illustrators of the golden age of book design and illustration in the first half of the 20th century”.</p> <p>“Fairytale watercolours by Nielsen rarely come on the market and we think that this is as good, or better, than any that have come up for sale in recent years,” said Albury. “It’s wonderfully translucent/vellucent and dripping in Chinese influence. Incredibly, Nielsen died in poverty and it’s really another case of posthumous world recognition arriving too late to feed the hungry artist.”</p> <p>The picture shows a Chinese girl standing under a willow tree by the river, listening to a nightingale sing – presumably the kitchen girl of Andersen’s story, who leads the Emperor of China’s staff to find the bird he is desperate to listen to.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"0b37ef666ed37e5cfabea4a72732b970cad5e976\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/0b37ef666ed37e5cfabea4a72732b970cad5e976/0_0_2772_3756/738.jpg\" alt=\"Full image of Kay Nielsen’s 1923 illustration to Hans Christian Andersen’s fairytale.\" width=\"738\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Full image of Kay Nielsen’s 1923 illustration to Hans Christian Andersen’s fairytale.</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>“I know it well; yes, indeed, how it can sing!” she says in the story, <a href=\"http://www.gutenberg.ca/ebooks/andersen-nightingale/andersen-nightingale-00-h.html\">first published in 1843</a>. “Every evening I have leave to carry home leavings from the table to my poor sick mother. She lives down by the shore, and when I’m coming back and am tired and take a rest in the wood, I hear the Nightingale sing. The tears come in my eyes with it: it feels as if my mother was kissing me.”</p> <p>The Emperor decides he prefers the song of a mechanical bird to that of the real nightingale, and it is exiled. But when the Emperor is dying, and the mechanical bird has broken, the real nightingale sings for him again, and he recovers.</p> <p>“At that instant there was heard, close by the window, the most lovely song. It was the little live Nightingale that was sitting on the branch outside. It had heard of its Emperor’s need, and so had come to sing to him of comfort and hope: and as it sung, the forms became more and more shadowy. The blood coursed quicker and quicker through the Emperor’s weak body, and Death himself listened and said: ‘Go on, little Nightingale! Go on.’”</p> <p>The story is believed to have been inspired by Anderson’s unrequited love for the opera singer Jenny Lind, said Dominic Winter. Albury added that “Andersen himself had in his youth been known as the Nightingale of Funen, all of which adds another layer to the meaning of the picture”.</p>","productionOffice":"UK","hasStoryPackage":"false","trailText":"Watercolour by Danish illustrator Kay Nielsen sells for £32,000","headline":"Very rare Hans Christian Andersen illustration sold at auction","byline":"Alison Flood","commentable":"true","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/0b37ef666ed37e5cfabea4a72732b970cad5e976/408_1793_1990_1194/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2015-12-24T00:00:00Z","standfirst":"<p>Watercolour by Danish illustrator Kay Nielsen sells for £32,000</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/dec/17/very-rare-hans-christian-andersen-illustration-up-for-auction-watercolour","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2015/dec/17/very-rare-hans-christian-andersen-illustration-up-for-auction-watercolour","sectionName":"Books","elements":[{"id":"0b37ef666ed37e5cfabea4a72732b970cad5e976","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/0b37ef666ed37e5cfabea4a72732b970cad5e976/408_1793_1990_1194/1000.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/0b37ef666ed37e5cfabea4a72732b970cad5e976","altText":"detail from Kay Nielsen’s 1923 illustration to Hans Christian Andersen’s The Nightingale.","caption":"‘Yes, indeed, how it can sing!’ ... detail from Kay Nielsen’s 1923 illustration to Hans Christian Andersen’s The Nightingale.","source":"PR","credit":"Photograph: PR","mediaId":"0b37ef666ed37e5cfabea4a72732b970cad5e976","displayCredit":"true","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/0b37ef666ed37e5cfabea4a72732b970cad5e976/408_1793_1990_1194/1000.jpg","width":"1000","height":"600"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/0b37ef666ed37e5cfabea4a72732b970cad5e976/408_1793_1990_1194/500.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/0b37ef666ed37e5cfabea4a72732b970cad5e976","altText":"detail from Kay Nielsen’s 1923 illustration to Hans Christian Andersen’s The N