[]},{"id":"books/books","webTitle":"Books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","webTitle":"Children and teenagers","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"culture/culture","webTitle":"Culture","type":"keyword","sectionId":"culture","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","sectionName":"Culture","references":[]},{"id":"artanddesign/illustration","webTitle":"Illustration","type":"keyword","sectionId":"artanddesign","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/illustration","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/artanddesign/illustration","sectionName":"Art and design","references":[]},{"id":"artanddesign/artanddesign","webTitle":"Art and design","type":"keyword","sectionId":"artanddesign","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/artanddesign","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/artanddesign/artanddesign","sectionName":"Art and design","references":[]},{"id":"artanddesign/design","webTitle":"Design","type":"keyword","sectionId":"artanddesign","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/design","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/artanddesign/design","sectionName":"Art and design","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"tone/news","webTitle":"News","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/news","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/news","references":[]},{"id":"profile/alisonflood","webTitle":"Alison Flood","r2ContributorId":"27440","bylineImageUrl":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/3/14/1300117336779/Alison.jpg","firstName":"","lastName":"flood","type":"contributor","bio":"<p>Alison Flood is a writer on guardian.co.uk/books and former news editor of the Bookseller</p>","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/alisonflood","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/profile/alisonflood","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"id":"stage/2015/dec/17/dr-seuss-the-lorax-old-vic-london-family-show-david-greig","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"type":"article","sectionId":"stage","webTitle":"Dr Seuss’s The Lorax review – the best family show since Matilda","webPublicationDate":"2015-12-17T12:42:49Z","fields":{"wordcount":"556","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4f6k6","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/gallery/2015/nov/26/lorax-christmas-dr-seusss-old-vic-in-pictures\">How the Lorax saved Christmas: Dr Seuss hits the Old Vic – in pictures</a> </p> </aside>  <p>One of the astonishing things about this children’s story by the prolific Theodor Seuss Geisel is its prescience: even in 1971, it was warning about the danger to the environment of unchecked capitalist growth. But this exhilarating adaptation by <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/davidgreig\">David Greig</a>, with songs by <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/may/05/noah-and-the-whale-interview\">Charlie Fink</a>, retains the original message without ever being preachy or pious. Its liberal spirit is balanced by a wonderful sense of impending anarchy.</p> <p>Greig stays true to the original fable. In ingeniously rhyming verse, he tells how the Once-ler was led into a betrayal of his friend, the Lorax, “a beavery thing” who speaks for the trees. Chancing upon the fruitful truffula tree, the antihero discovers its tufts yield a multipurpose product called a “thneed” for which there turns out to be a big market. Soon the Once-ler turns into a mad axeman chopping down whole forests and building factories in order to satisfy voracious demand. But, while the balance of nature is disturbed, the story offers a sliver of hope in a cryptic clue left by the bereft Lorax.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"ea9a674376420f2c4f621d89d0c3687a647e7041\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/ea9a674376420f2c4f621d89d0c3687a647e7041/578_490_3740_2245/1000.jpg\" alt=\"The Lorax by Dr Seuss at the Old Vic.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Simon Paisley Day (Once-ler) in The Lorax by Dr Seuss at the Old Vic.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Tristram Kenton for the Guardian</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>In adapting the story for the stage, Greig has enriched it by making the Once-ler infinitely more than a predatory villain. Played by Simon Paisley Day with a leaping enthusiasm and comic verve that inescapably reminds one of John Cleese, he is a naive dreamer sucked into the vortex of rampant consumerism. In this version, he is also a green-haired victim of his materialist family, trickster lawyers and a society that believes, in the spirit of Wall Street’s Gordon Gekko, that greed is good. One of Greig’s most telling inventions is a scene where Paisley Day, in a fashionable nod to transparency, invites the TV cameras in to his factories, only for them to be revealed as a source of smoggy pollution. The Once-ler also reminds us that if “we biggered your cars and freezers and fridges”, it was because the world demands constant growth. </p> <p>While Greig has lent the fable a measure of ambivalence, what enchants is the inventiveness of Fink’s music, Finn Caldwell’s puppetry, Rob Howell’s designs and Max Webster’s production. The songs cover every style from political protest to Motown mashup, with Melanie La Barrie buoyantly leading a Supremes-style number appealing to the Once-ler’s desire for greatness. The Lorax, artfully manipulated by Simon Lipkin, Laura Cubitt and Ben Thompson, is also an infinitely beguiling, droopy-moustached creature with the faint pathos of the liberal optimist. Rob Howell also excels himself with designs that range from the rainbow-hued beauty of the towering truffula trees to the monstrosity of the Once-ler factory, where the automatic knitters spew out filthy gloop.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"a03efa0239eac6b2fbfa590e52364b9ef1486bd5\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/a03efa0239eac6b2fbfa590e52364b9ef1486bd5/161_319_3362_2017/1000.jpg\" alt=\"The Lorax by Dr Seuss at the Old Vic\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">The Lorax by Dr Seuss at the Old Vic</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Tristram Kenton for the Guardian</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>In the end, the show appeals to our imagination without, like one or two seasonal entertainments, sating it. It also points out a moral without hitting us over the head with its good intentions. One of Greig’s cleverest touches is to show the Once-ler, in a sop to ecological protest, creating a nature reserve that will coral the animals while simultaneously announcing “You want five million thneeds for the people of Sweden? We’ll make those thneeds and some more if you need em!” In its mixture of verbal wit and social purpose, this is the best family show since Matilda.</p> <ul> <li><a href=\"http://www.oldvictheatre.com/whats-on/2015/the-lorax/\">At Old Vic, London,</a> until 16 January. Box office: 0844-871 7628. <br /></li> </ul>","productionOffice":"UK","hasStoryPackage":"false","trailText":"David Greig’s anarchic take on the ecological analogy – where greed increases the need for ‘thneeds’ – is full of verbal wit and social purpose","starRating":"5","headline":"Dr Seuss’s The Lorax review – the best family show since Matilda","byline":"Michael Billington","commentable":"true","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/f69f29b0c37f0e3521a658d2b9fc06e64e2de435/41_363_4420_2652/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2015-12-20T12:45:00Z","standfirst":"<p><strong>Old Vic, London<br></strong>David Greig’s anarchic take on the ecological analogy – where greed increases the need for ‘thneeds’ – is full of verbal wit and social purpose</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2015/dec/17/dr-seuss-the-lorax-old-vic-london-family-show-david-greig","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/stage/2015/dec/17/dr-seuss-the-lorax-old-vic-london-family-show-david-greig","sectionName":"Stage","elements":[{"id":"f69f29b0c37f0e3521a658d2b9fc06e64e2de435","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/f69f29b0c37f0e3521a658d2b9fc06e64e2de435/41_363_4420_2652/140.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"©Tristram Kenton","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/f69f29b0c37f0e3521a658d2b9fc06e64e2de435","altText":"The Lorax by Dr Seuss at the Old Vic.","caption":"Emily Houghton (Donkey) and Simon Paisley Day (Once-ler), Laura Cubitt and Simon Lipkin in The Lorax by Dr Seuss at the Old Vic.","source":"Tristram Kenton for the Guardian","credit":"Photograph: Tristram Kenton for the Guardian","mediaId":"f69f29b0c37f0e3521a658d2b9fc06e64e2de435","displayCredit":"true","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/f69f29b0c37f0e3521a658d2b9fc06e64e2de435/41_363_4420_2652/140.jpg","width":"140","height":"84"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/f69f29b0c37f0e3521a658d2b9fc06e64e2de435/41_363_4420_2652/500.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"©Tristram Kenton","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/f69f29b0c37f0e3521a658d2b9fc06e64e2de435","altText":"The Lorax by Dr Seuss at the Old Vic.","caption":"Emily Houghton (Donkey) and Simon Paisley Day (Once-ler)