ardian.com/books/childrens-books-8-12-years","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/childrens-books-8-12-years","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"childrens-books-site/series/greatest-quotes-ever","webTitle":"Greatest quotes ever","description":"The best quotes from your favourite children's and teen authors ","type":"series","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/series/greatest-quotes-ever","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/series/greatest-quotes-ever","sectionName":"Children's books","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"id":"books/2015/dec/17/the-bedside-guardian-2015-edited-malik-meer-review","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"type":"article","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"The Bedside Guardian 2015, edited by Malik Meer review – ‘unique, touching, provocative’","webPublicationDate":"2015-12-17T07:30:12Z","fields":{"wordcount":"1002","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4f3ym","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p>As regular as Christmas – “It can’t be <em>The</em> <em>Bedside Guardian</em> already!” – here it is again, this unique, touching, provocative compendium that is at once an account of the year itself and of the Guardian’s year. 2015 (or more precisely autumn 2014 to autumn 2015) was a particularly vivid, unsettling year both for Britain and for the paper. In June, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/alanrusbridger\" title=\"\">Alan Rusbridger</a>’s 20-year tenure as editor came to an end and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/katharineviner\" title=\"\">Katharine Viner</a> took over. Rusbridger’s “Farewell to my readers” is, in a sense, the centrepiece of the book, unexpectedly affecting in its quietly spoken rejection of editorial imperialism and its parallel embrace of the changed post-internet relationship with readers. He identifies the current Guardian as having directly evolved out of the great Manchester original and the Scott Trust, set up by CP Scott, the first editor, of which Rusbridger will become chair in September 2016, as its foundation and the source of its independence. The trust has allowed it to create an identity that is beholden neither to proprietors nor political parties, but to a consciously developed worldview that permeates the entire organisation. A “kindly rival” took Rusbridger for lunch just after he had become editor, and told him that if he were ever absent, there were six assistant editors who had different views of what his paper should be. “If you take a day off, the building itself would produce the Guardian.”</p> <p>The year covered by the book has been a challenging one for the world, and in particular for those of us who share the Guardian’s sensibilities. Climate change continued apace, unchecked by wavering politicians, while deniers remained maddeningly vocal and undeterred; the Labour vote collapsed under Ed Miliband; the Syrian situation continued on its bloody path; immigrants in their hundreds of thousands clawed a desperate route to the perceived promised lands of Europe, Islamist gunmen assailed Paris, slaughtering 12 cartoonists (the subsequent attacks are not covered here); and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/jeremy-corbyn\" title=\"\">Jeremy Corbyn</a> swept to entirely unpredicted power, taking left, right and centre aback.</p> <p>Much of this is touched on in <em>The  Bedside Guardian</em>. As befits “this  extraordinary agent of reporting, argument, investigation, questioning and advocacy” (Rusbridger again, in his piece on climate change), the book comes at it from all sides. There are the expected certainties – <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/paul-krugman\" title=\"\">Paul Krugman</a> on the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/ng-interactive/2015/apr/29/the-austerity-delusion\" title=\"\">folly of austerity</a> is almost surreally doubt-free – as well as hard reportage from <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/martin-chulov\" title=\"\">Martin Chulov</a> on the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/dec/11/-sp-isis-the-inside-story\" title=\"\">origins of Isis</a>, and striking analysis from <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/paul-mason\" title=\"\">Paul Mason</a> on the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/apr/06/marxist-theory-game-of-thrones-lannisters-bankers-sex-power-feudal-westeros-revolution\" title=\"\">fall of feudalism </a>as portrayed in <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/game-of-thrones\" title=\"\"><em>Game of Thrones</em></a>. Even more characteristic of the paper are the undecided pieces, full of doubt and paradox: <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/zoewilliams\" title=\"\">Zoe Williams</a> on the matter of Uber cars versus black cabs (no verdict); <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/alexispetridis\" title=\"\">Alexis Petridis</a>, on the harassed rump of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/mar/01/gary-glitter-fans-paul-gadd-facebook\" title=\"\">Gary Glitter fans</a> (fascinated bewilderment); and, best of all, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/jonathanfreedland\" title=\"\">Jonathan Freedland</a> on <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/charlie-hebdo\" title=\"\">Charlie Hebdo</a> (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/jan/09/charlie-hebdo-cartoonists-paris-killers-fascist-death-cult\" title=\"\">“First they came for the cartoonists, then they came for the Jews”</a>), a piece of exquisitely complex soul-searching, uncomfortably unresolved. Freedland speaks for all of us.</p> <p>It is obviously impossible to include everything that makes the Guardian what it is. There is a feisty foreword by <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/naomiklein\" title=\"\">Naomi Klein</a>, which focuses on the paper’s campaigning aspect, praising its courage – “in the face of the most urgent crises we face as a human family” – in declaring the unacceptability of what she calls “normalised abuses … of people, privacy and planet”. Malik Meer, the Guardian’s features editor, has made the selection, and there isn’t a single one of the more than 80 pieces that doesn’t engage and reward the attention. If I had a cavil, it would be the scant attention paid to the arts, an area in which the Guardian has outdone most of its competitors in maintaining broad and deep coverage, treating the theatre, books, art and music as if they were a crucial part of the discourse of our times. There is a sharp comment on the long-closeted prequel to <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/harper-lee\" title=\"\">Harper Lee</a>’s <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/to-kill-a-mockingbird.html\" title=\"\"><em>To Kill a Mockingbird</em></a>, an elegant homage to the late <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/omar-sharif\" title=\"\">Omar Sharif</a>, a quizzical piece about <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/bill-murray\" title=\"\">Bill Murray</a> and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/nancybankssmith\" title=\"\">Nancy Banks-Smith</a>’s <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/jan/20/nancy-banks-smith-on-deirdre-barlow-anne-kirkbride-coronation-street\" title=\"\">magnificent obituary of Deirdre</a> from <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/coronation-street\" title=\"\"><em>Coronation Street</em></a> – and that’s it. This is doubly disappointing: first, because of the quality of so much arts writing in the paper, and, second, because the book’s account of the year is incomplete without it.</p> <p>Meer ends the collection gloriously with a small masterpiece, “All Hail the Bearded One”, a speculative account by <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/chris-mullin\" title=\"\">Chris Mullin</a> of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/sep/14/prime-minister-jeremy-corbyn-the-first-100-days\" title=\"\">Corbyn’s first 100 days in office</a>. It is both fantastical and profound, credibly outlining a series of unlikely events that result both in Corbyn’s election and the subsequent triumph of his administration. But the beauty of the piece is that it is predicated on an assumption of generosity, humanity and good humour on the part of the British electorate. It is in fact a masterly little example of that rare genre – utopian writing – and reminds us that the Guardian, for all it its progressiveness, technologically, politically and socially, is a newspaper deeply rooted in the utopian socialism of the end of the 19th century, which makes it both passionate and benevolent, a most uncommon combination. <em>The Bedside Guardian 2015</em> is also, of course, a book, celebrating within hard covers the most notoriously ephemeral branch of the profession of letters. It is a book that will, I suspect, be read for some time ahead, as testimony both of who we were in 2015 and what we believed in.</p> <p>• Simon Callow’s <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/346161/s/orson-welles-one-man-band/\" title=\"\"><em>Orson Welles: One-Man Band</em></a> is published by Jonathan Cape. To order<strong> </strong><em>The Bedside Guardian 2015</em><strong> </strong>for £9.99 (RRP £14.99) go to <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/357557/?utm_source=editoriallink&amp;utm_medium=merch&amp;utm_campaign=article\" title=\"\">bookshop.theguardian.com</a> or call 0330 333 6846. Free UK p&amp;p over £10, online orders only. Phone orders min p&amp;p of £1.99.</p>","productionOffice":"UK","hasStoryPackage":"false","trailText":"From Isis to Uber, Charlie Hebdo to Jeremy Corbyn: an engaging guide to a challenging year","headline":"The Bedside Guardian 2015, edited by Malik Meer review – ‘unique, touching, provocative’","byline":"Simon Callow","commentable":"true","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/5465084bb71371971e97efffbe1c2247471314ad/0_125_4924_2954/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-01-29T12:11:00Z","standfirst":"<p>From Isis to Uber, Charlie Hebdo to Jeremy Corbyn: an engaging guide to a challenging year</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/dec/17/the-bedside-guardian-2015-edited-malik-meer-review","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2015/dec/17/the-bedside-guardian-2015-edited-malik-meer-review","sectionName":"Books","elements":[{"id":"5465084bb71371971e97efffbe1c2247471314ad","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/5465084bb71371971e97efffbe1c2247471314ad/0_0_4924_3155/2000.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"© David Levene 2015","picdarUrn":"GD*53107331","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/5465084bb71371971e97efffbe1c2247471314ad","altText":"The Guardian’s current editor Kath Viner with former editor Alan Rusbridger.","caption":"This year saw Kath Viner take over from Alan Rusbridger as editor of the Guardian. ","photographer":"David Levene","source":"The Guardian","credit":"Photograph: David Levene for the Guardian","mediaId":"5465084bb71371971e97efffbe1c2247471314ad","displayCredit":"true","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/5465084bb71371971e97efffbe1c2247471314ad/0_0_4924_3155/2000.jpg","width":"2000","height":"1281"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/5465084bb71371971e97efffbe1c2247471314ad/0_0_4924_3155/1000.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"© David Levene 2015","picdarUrn":"GD*53107331","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/5465084bb71371971e97efffbe1c2247471314ad","altText":"The Guardian’s current editor Kath Viner with former editor Alan Rusbridger.","caption":"This year saw Kath Viner take over from Alan Rusbridger as editor of the Guardian. ","photographer":"David Levene","source":"The Guardian","credit":