torId":"27440","bylineImageUrl":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/3/14/1300117336779/Alison.jpg","firstName":"","lastName":"flood","type":"contributor","bio":"<p>Alison Flood is a writer on guardian.co.uk/books and former news editor of the Bookseller</p>","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/alisonflood","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/profile/alisonflood","references":[]},{"id":"publication/theguardian","webTitle":"The Guardian","type":"publication","sectionId":"theguardian","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/all","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/publication/theguardian","sectionName":"From the Guardian","references":[]},{"id":"theguardian/mainsection","webTitle":"Main section","type":"newspaper-book","sectionId":"news","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/mainsection","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/mainsection","sectionName":"News","references":[]},{"id":"theguardian/mainsection/uknews","webTitle":"UK news","type":"newspaper-book-section","sectionId":"uk-news","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/mainsection/uknews","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/mainsection/uknews","sectionName":"UK news","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"id":"books/2015/dec/16/drew-barrymore-wildflower-review-guarded-little-girl-lost","rights":{"syndicatable":"false"},"type":"article","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Wildflower by Drew Barrymore review – too guarded to be revealing","webPublicationDate":"2015-12-16T19:33:02Z","fields":{"wordcount":"920","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4f57b","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p>The pull quote on the back of the paperback edition of actress Drew Barrymore’s memoir <a href=\"http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/58658.Little_Girl_Lost\">Little Girl Lost</a>, co-authored with journalist <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Todd-Gold/e/B001ITYC0Q\">Todd Gold</a> and published in 1990 when she was just 15, doesn’t beat around the bush: “I had my first drink at age nine, began smoking marijuana at 10, and at 12 took up cocaine.” </p> <p>As a woman on the cusp of 40, I’m just about Barrymore’s age. I remember with some clarity huddling on the grey-carpeted floor of a mall bookstore at 14, worried but fascinated, scanning the book’s pages for ever-more-concerning details, details whose shock value was predicated on the disjoint between the public perception of Barrymore as the adorable moppet of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/et-the-extra-terrestrial\">Spielberg’s ET</a>, and the no-rules, too-much-too-soon narrative of familial dysfunction and Hollywood debauchery that was apparently taking place behind that winsome, blond-and-white-and-pink façade. </p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/2015/oct/25/drew-barrymore-mother-locked-up-in-institution-interview\">Drew Barrymore: ‘My mother locked me up in an institution at 13. Boo hoo! I needed it’</a> </p> </aside>  <p>With a mother who set few boundaries and relied on her as a breadwinner starting when she was just a baby, and an absent, out-of-his-mind father (a scion of the storied but troubled Barrymore acting clan), the odds seemed stacked against Barrymore. And like many others in America at the time, I felt more than a little invested in her wellbeing. It almost seemed as if the health of the body politic was linked in some obscure but still palpable way to the health of Barrymore herself, that golden-haired eternal child who should have been better protected so as to remain our image of perfect innocence. </p> <p>A couple of years after reading Little Girl Lost, I saw <a href=\"http://36.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_m02yh52PdJ1qzn70jo2_400.jpg\">Barrymore in an Interview magazine spread</a> where she was photographed bare-breasted and smoking. Although I was by then a teen smoker who wouldn’t have minded baring her own breasts had anyone asked, so insidious was the old Barrymore fantasy that I actually felt alarmed. Did Drew know what she was doing? Was anyone looking out for her? Would things be all right?<br /></p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"ccc0dc5d6bf85f42c42f9fbcad4a1e807d6aee65\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/ccc0dc5d6bf85f42c42f9fbcad4a1e807d6aee65/0_764_3840_2301/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Drew Barrymore\" width=\"1000\" height=\"599\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Drew Barrymore.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Danielle Levitt for the Guardian</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Over the past 25 years, Barrymore has become a successful actor, movie producer, beauty-company cofounder, even the entrepreneur behind <a href=\"http://www.barrymorewines.com/\">a boutique wine label</a>, as well as a wife and mother of two young daughters. This newfound stability, however, poses a problem for her recent memoir, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/2015/oct/25/drew-barrymore-the-day-i-divorced-my-mother\">Wildflower</a>. It is missing those elements of truth in suffering that had pulled us into her younger life in Little Girl Lost. </p> <p>This feels like a missed opportunity, since Barrymore conceivably still has a pretty big story to tell in this follow-up book. Even for those who may not be as nosily fascinated as myself in the minutiae of her Hollywood love affairs over the years (<a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2250146/Drew-Barrymore-Star-says-ex-boyfriend-Fabrizio-Moretti-perfect-match-Kirstin-Wiig.html\">Fabrizio Moretti</a> of the Strokes! Eric Erlandson of Hole! That random make-out session with Gossip Girl’s Ed Westwick back in 2008!), there’s so much left to examine. Chiefly, this: how did the parentless, bereft child of the late 80s become the stable, prosperous mogul of the 2010s?</p> <p>To be fair, Barrymore does note from the start that she’s not interested in writing a sweeping memoir that would give a full account of her life. In fact, “‘Memoir’ seems heavy to me, and I want this to be light,’’ she opines in the preface. “This is a book you can dip into and read when you want.” Working non-chronologically and touching on moments from her childhood as well as adulthood, Barrymore uses a recurring format: a brief recounting of a story from her past, with its end rounded out with some sort of lesson she has learned from that experience, more often than not figured in a writing relentless with exclamation marks. </p> <p>In a section about growing up essentially fatherless, for instance: “A stable, loving family is something that should absolutely, fundamentally never ever be taken for granted! I am lucky that I got dealt some cards that showed me what it’s like to not have a family, and I am much luckier to now have the chance to create my own deck! I will fight like William ‘Braveheart’ what’s-his-name to keep [my daughters] protected and intact! I am a warrior. I am a soldier. I am a not-to-be-messed-with lion! I am a mother!” </p> <p>There is more than a dollop of bootstrappy self-help in the book (about success in business: “I have an insane work ethic! I am strict with myself. I’m trained to work. I don’t know life without it. ... You have to kill yourself. Do your homework. Exhaust yourself.”) We also get some bland stories of Barrymore’s friendships and relationships (skydiving with Cameron Diaz; shenanigans on a road trip with her best friend and producing partner Nancy Juvonen; a pancake-making session gone wrong with her fiancé, now-husband), none of which are particularly revealing. There are some nice, loving missives Barrymore addresses to her young daughters, but it’s not totally clear why these should be shared in a book rather than simply given to them.</p> <p>I’m happy for Barrymore, I really am. She’s clearly made it to the other side of a horrible childhood, which couldn’t have been easy, and there’s something appealing about her palpable desire to do better, to not repeat the patterns that made her young life so miserable and risky. But writing, too, means taking risks and having something to lose, and in this pat book, almost hysterical in its need to project a safe sunniness, Barrymore tells us precious little about who she really is or about how she got from there to here. </p>","productionOffice":"US","hasStoryPackage":"false","trailText":"Her first memoir, Little Girl Lost, had a cult status in the 1980s, but this follow-up is missing the elements of truth that made the previous book so compelling","headline":"Wildflower by Drew Barrymore review – too guarded to be revealing","byline":"Naomi Fry","commentable":"true","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/43ebee4c7791f7d9d2520dc051e9cb37fad5b7c1/0_89_2000_1200/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2015-12-19T19:30:00Z","standfirst":"<p>Her first memoir, Little Girl Lost, had a cult status in the 1980s, but this follow-up is missing the elements of truth that made the previous book so compelling</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/dec/16/drew-barrymore-wildflower-review-guarded-little-girl-lost","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2015/dec/16/drew-barrymore-wildflower-review-guarded-little-girl-lost","sectionName":"Books","elements":[{"id":"43ebee4c7791f7d9d2520dc051e9cb37fad5b7c1","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/43ebee4c7791f7d9d2520dc051e9cb37fad5b7c1/0_89_2000_1200/2000.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"1995 CBS Photo Archive","picdarUrn":"GD*52252762","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/43ebee4c7791f7d9d2520dc051e9cb37fad5b7c1","altText":"Drew Barrymore, in her wilder days, shocking David Letterman.","caption":"Drew Barrymore, in her wilder days, shocking David Letterman.","photographer":"CBS Photo Archive","source":"CBS via Getty Images","credit":"Photograph: CBS Photo Archive/CBS via Getty Images","medi